{"questionId":"21824","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The amount, in milligrams, of a medicinal drug in the body <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi></math> hours after it was injected is&nbsp;given by <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>D</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>t</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>23</mn><mo>(</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>85</mn><msup><mo>)</mo><mi>t</mi></msup><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>t</mi><mo>≥</mo><mn>0</mn></math>. Before this injection, the amount of the drug in the body&nbsp;was zero.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Write down</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>the initial dose of the drug.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>23</mn><mo> </mo><mtext>mg</mtext></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><em><strong><br>[1 mark]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"21824","referenceCode":"21M.1.SL.TZ2.1a.i","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"the initial dose of the drug.","paper":"1","level":"SL","questionNumber":"a.i","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 2—Functions","Topic 2—Functions","SL 2.5—Modelling functions"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}